                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Tenaiya</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/10/2003&nbsp;: 07:53:47 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Hmmmm...yes, I did forget about Dot stacking (but then again, that was why I said "Did I forget anything?"). That bit of balancing did make us balanced with regards to the other casters in the sense that we could stack necros like wizzies could be stacked. However, the point is: we are still slightly sub-par in certain respects, especially in the mana/damage ratio department. Sure, they had to take into account our mana regen when deciding the mana costs of our spells, but I don't think it really makes sense that a spell that takes longer to do less damage should cost more mana.<br /><br />Focus items really didn't make that much of an impact on the game when they were released, especially for necros. I stand by my opinion that the only focus effect that really did anything for necros balancewise was affliction efficiency. There were no corresponding effects to the DD-improving foci, extended affliction was an almost laughable attempt. I seriously can't believe that they thought that all those foci would affect dots in any meaningful way. In any case, focus effects really only came into the limelight after PoP was released and they flooded the game with focus items. Prior to that, most useful high end focus items were not particularly accessible to the majority of casters on any server. How was that supposed to help make casters more balanced?<br /><br />As for resist changes, as far as I'm aware, there were 2 changes. The first was that pets would use the resists of their owner if it was higher than their natural resists. This was good, if marginally useful. Unfortunately, they then decided to revamp the entire resist scale. Our spells which originally landed on mobs without any problems (Splurt anyone?) suddenly became resisted perhaps 1 in 6 times. Our own resists, on the other hand, became all-or-nothing affairs: if you couldn't get your resists to 300, there was no point in trying to up your resists anyway because even piddly little HoT-type AEs would land on you. That pretty much took care of whatever resist advantages our pets got.<br /><br />Critical nukes were added only to wizards. All other classes had to buy them in the form of AA. Therefore, it was not balancing in and of itself. First of all, it required that a player bought an expansion before they could get the skill. Then the other classes all had to dump valuable experience into buying the skill; balance should be class inherent. Next, given that our crit nukes barely equal uncritted wizzie/mage nukes, how exactly did that help us be more balanced? Finally, our main 'damage theme' is damage-over-time spells. The idea of crit nukes is at odds with with our main theme and therefore doesn't make us more balanced but instead more conflicted. So instead of focusing on our dotting abilities, we end up getting a mish mash of dots and nukes (but nukes that must do less damage than wizzie or mage nukes).<br /><br />Don't get me wrong, I'm fairly happy with the state necros are in. Further improvements would just be nice touches to further round us up and to make things make more sense (nukes doing more instant damage while costing less mana is something that gets me pretty annoyed). But I remain unconvinced that caster balancing was even halfway complete. I won't, however, argue that the pure melee classes are in need of more immediate patching up.</span></font></td>
